uot;:null,&quot;title&quot;:null,&quot;type&quot;:&quot;image/png&quot;,&quot;href&quot;:null,&quot;belowTheFold&quot;:false,&quot;topImage&quot;:true,&quot;internalRedirect&quot;:null,&quot;isProcessing&quot;:false,&quot;align&quot;:null,&quot;offset&quot;:false}\" class=\"sizing-normal\" alt=\"\" srcset=\"https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/$s_!Fmkt!,w_424,c_limit,f_auto,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2F17c47be6-7a35-4110-8745-a8e005630a77_1100x872.png 424w, https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/$s_!Fmkt!,w_848,c_limit,f_auto,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2F17c47be6-7a35-4110-8745-a8e005630a77_1100x872.png 848w, https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/$s_!Fmkt!,w_1272,c_limit,f_auto,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2F17c47be6-7a35-4110-8745-a8e005630a77_1100x872.png 1272w, https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/$s_!Fmkt!,w_1456,c_limit,f_auto,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2F17c47be6-7a35-4110-8745-a8e005630a77_1100x872.png 1456w\" sizes=\"100vw\" fetchpriority=\"high\"></picture><div class=\"image-link-expand\"><div class=\"pencraft pc-display-flex pc-gap-8 pc-reset\"><button tabindex=\"0\" type=\"button\" class=\"pencraft pc-reset pencraft icon-container restack-image\"><svg role=\"img\" width=\"20\" height=\"20\" viewBox=\"0 0 20 20\" fill=\"none\" stroke-width=\"1.5\" stroke=\"var(--color-fg-primary)\" stroke-linecap=\"round\" stroke-linejoin=\"round\" xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/2000/svg\"><g><title></title><path d=\"M2.53001 7.81595C3.49179 4.73911 6.43281 2.5 9.91173 2.5C13.1684 2.5 15.9537 4.46214 17.0852 7.23684L17.6179 8.67647M17.6179 8.67647L18.5002 4.26471M17.6179 8.67647L13.6473 6.91176M17.4995 12.1841C16.5378 15.2609 13.5967 17.5 10.1178 17.5C6.86118 17.5 4.07589 15.5379 2.94432 12.7632L2.41165 11.3235M2.41165 11.3235L1.5293 15.7353M2.41165 11.3235L6.38224 13.0882\"></path></g></svg></button><button tabindex=\"0\" type=\"button\" class=\"pencraft pc-reset pencraft icon-container view-image\"><svg xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/2000/svg\" width=\"20\" height=\"20\" viewBox=\"0 0 24 24\" fill=\"none\" stroke=\"currentColor\" stroke-width=\"2\" stroke-linecap=\"round\" stroke-linejoin=\"round\" class=\"lucide lucide-maximize2 lucide-maximize-2\"><polyline points=\"15 3 21 3 21 9\"></polyline><polyline points=\"9 21 3 21 3 15\"></polyline><line x1=\"21\" x2=\"14\" y1=\"3\" y2=\"10\"></line><line x1=\"3\" x2=\"10\" y1=\"21\" y2=\"14\"></line></svg></button></div></div></div></a></figure></div><p></p><p>Ever find having casual conversations difficult? I don\u2019t think you should blame yourself. Rather than \u2018introversion\u2019 or \u2018shyness\u2019, I actually think this feeling comes from a systemic issue with <em>conversation itself, </em>that no one really talks about<em>. </em>Let me give a bit of background and explain. </p><div><hr></div><p>In spoken conversations, I get moments where I try to find something to say, but can\u2019t. My ideas suddenly lock up, like a sink clogged by cold oil. </p><p>When I am on my own - thinking or writing - my brain swims in a nice coral reef. There are colours, shapes, and ideas that I can latch onto. My mind\u2019s eye sees a crisp scenery of thoughts. </p><p>But when I am talking to someone, that coral reef can sometimes turn into a wide, monochromatic ocean. At that point, I\u2019m trying to look hard for features and things to say. </p><p>For me, this can happen with friends I have known for more than a decade. Or at family functions. Or with strangers. The effect doesn\u2019t discriminate. </p><p>Much like people who fear open oceans, I get anxious when I blank out like this. Then like a recursive loop, I get stressed about being stressed, out of self frustration. Who doesn\u2019t kick themselves about not being socially able? And then after that, I get stressed about being too hard on myself. And the cycle continues, till infinity. </p><p>Unfortunately, this sometimes ends in me politely saying that I need to wash my hands or something, thereby excusing myself from the conversation. Which is a shame.  </p><p>I\u2019ve ignored this truth about my shit conversation skills for years. I\u2019m in my late-twenties now, and it hasn\u2019t really gotten better. And self-help books don\u2019t work because speaking to someone with guidelines doesn\u2019t really get to the heart of the issue. </p><p>But now, I feel like writing essays has given me some clarity of thought on how conversations work.</p><p>You see, most people place conversation anxiety as a symptom of \u2018shyness\u2019. </p><p>But I think this is really wrong. Whilst I find conversations difficult, I\u2019m actually not that shy as a person. I have quite a few friends. I regularly go to house parties and sometimes to clubs. So I don\u2019t think it\u2019s fair to build any correlation with how shy someone is with how well they can hold a conversation. The opposite way round is true as well. I also know plenty of introverts, people considered shy, that hold conversations exceptionally well. </p><p>So why do I get paralysed when I speak? Well, I think it\u2019s actually just systemic feature of the spoken word. Conversation as a medium of idea exchange <em>is</em> <em>just bad</em>. </p><p>It\u2019s bad because words are highly ambiguous tools to communicate. And so, short sentences found in casual conversation don\u2019t allow for a crisp exchange of ideas between people. And so, people like me who find ambiguity hard, have a crap time having conversations. Let me convince you why this is the case. </p><p>In my short time writing essays, I\u2019ve realised that words are much more ambiguous than I thought. This is because most people portray ideas with words that describe their state of mind, rather than illustrate real world states that the ideas are linked to. The issue with using words that describe your state of mind, is that only <strong>YOU</strong> know what you really mean. </p><p>Despite being a mathematician, I\u2019ve really learnt this fact from the creative writing community. </p><p>I\u2019ve been trying to improve how accurately I portray an idea to my readers. One of the main pieces of advice I hear on the writer\u2019s reddit is \u2018showing not telling\u2019. </p><p>Instead of writing something or saying something like \u2018he was mad\u2019, it\u2019s better to <em>show</em> it. That means describing real, mechanistic actions that the reader can visualise in the real world. For instance, \u2018he smashed his fist against the wall\u2019, or, \u2018he walked off quickly\u2019. </p><p>This reminds me a lot of what Murakami wrote in his memoir. A lot of writers\u2019 time is thinking about ways where you can say \u2018for instance\u2019. And with each different way to show it, you are selecting a different <em>shade</em> of emotion. Smashing one\u2019s fist against the wall communicates a quick, aggressive temper. Whereas walking off quickly can imply a more avoidant personality type. </p><p>And so in conversation, short sentences mean that the speaker is presenting an album of thousands of different images for the me to chose, and only one of those reflects the one that they really mean. It\u2019s like trying to select the right card from a face down deck. The more \u2018showing there is\u2019 in a string of sentences, the more that deck of cards is eliminated, and the crisper the idea is. </p><p>But this is<strong> why conversations are hard</strong>. Conversations usually consist of two or more people saying a couple of sentences back and forth. <strong>So there </strong><em><strong>isn\u2019t space</strong></em><strong> to \u2018show and not tell\u2019.</strong></p><p>And I don\u2019t want to piss off who I\u2019m talking to by always interrupting with a \u2018can you give me an example?\u2019. Instead of saying \u2018this is nice apple crumble\u2019, I would rather hear something like \u2018the texture is crunchier than most other apple crumble places around here!\u2019. Honestly, I wish more people would think about this, because it would increase the dimensionality of questions I could follow up on. </p><p>And in the same vein, I think \u2018knowing someone well is a measure of how you can \u2018trade images\u2019 with each other with less words. </p><p>So why are some people better at conversations that others? Well, with this model, I think that these people are just more comfortable in accepting the ambiguity of the spoken word. But being more comfortable with uncertainty is a really different question to not being shy. So, don\u2019t be so hard on yourself.</p><p>Happy holidays, and good luck with the family functions!</p>",
